# Comment Contract

This repository intentionally prefers richer comments than typical Go code when they preserve context future agents and maintainers would otherwise lose.

## Add comments when code is non-obvious
Prefer comments around:
- concurrency and lifecycle coordination
- data integrity assumptions
- retries, timeouts, and idempotency rules
- protocol or spec edge cases
- package boundaries and dependency constraints
- trade-offs where a simpler-looking alternative was intentionally rejected

## Good comment content
Comments should preserve:
- why the code exists
- invariants it must preserve
- failure and recovery behavior
- design trade-offs
- TODO owner decisions that materially affect later amendments

## Avoid low-value comments
Do not narrate obvious syntax or restate the code mechanically.
